          "body": "What follows the diagnosis is not triumphalism but tears. Isaiah weeps bitterly for Jazer (16:9), drenches Heshbon and Elealeh with his own tears (16:9), and describes his heart as intoning like a harp for Moab, his 'inward feelings' (literally 'bowels,' meeh) for Kir-hareseth (16:11). The emotional register is the most intense in the Moab oracle and rivals the grief of Jeremiah 48, which borrows this passage almost verbatim. The chapter mourns Sibmah's legendary vines — once reaching to Jazer and the desert and the sea, emblems of Moab's commercial glory — now trampled by foreign rulers (16:8). The harvest shouts are silenced; the winepress is empty; God Himself says 'I have made the shouting to cease' (16:10). That last phrase is the theological key to the lament: Isaiah's tears do not contradict God's sovereignty — they express the grief of one who has learned to grieve what God judges. This is the prophetic pathos that Heschel identifies as the heartbeat of the prophetic calling: feeling the weight of God's own pain over the destruction His justice requires. Spurgeon noted that those most conformed to Christ are those who can weep over the cities — and enemies — that will be destroyed."
